Lebanon's Comprehensive Crisis
Beirut — Looking back, it's usually the case that before a financial crisis occurs, there are apparent signs; however, they rarely clearly indicate the course of history.
The situation in Lebanon is the same now, with a predictable crisis having plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since the end of the long civil war in Lebanon (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been sustained by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, the inflow of external capital had to come to a halt. This turning point arrived in late 2019, marked by a series of consecutive negative shocks.
This "sudden stop" of capital brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit reached as high as 25 percent of its gross domestic product, and its export base was too small to even cover the costs of necessary imports.
The second issue is finance.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of economic recession, with the budget deficit already substantial, reaching 10% of GDP in 2019 and continuing to expand rapidly.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, as the primary recipients of foreign capital inflows, have invested heavily in Lebanon's sovereign debt (accounting on average for 50% of their portfolios), and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises pushed Lebanon's economy into the depths of despair.
Companies that desire loans and imports have started laying off workers or shutting down completely.
An economic recession could lead to a Lebanese depression.
The primary source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic situation is not oil, but rather the diaspora, who are attracted to invest due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate pegged to the US dollar.
It's no wonder there are signs of "Dutch disease" everywhere: savings have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has driven the national savings rate down to an unlikely level — just 3% of GDP.
The level of inequality is very high and is still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50 percent, significantly weakening the tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of export goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated young people.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than merit.
These elites siphoned off wealth from both the public and private sectors to establish a bloated clique-dominated ruling group.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even the power supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the broader macroeconomic challenges have remained completely unresolved.
The financial crisis sparked a political uprising.
A mass movement of popular revolution took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country's regime has consistently responded to Lebanon's economic issues in a manner that overwhelmingly favors the elite, indicating that the crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, thereby further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the state refuses to introduce capital controls, allowing the major shareholders of each bank—including politicians in power—to decide how to quantitatively withdraw cash.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens find it difficult to access deposits.
In addition, the central bank reduced deposit rates but has not yet lowered public debt rates, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon has continued to repay its major foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are indications that it may have started selling state-owned assets to elite affiliated entities at fire-sale prices.
At the same time, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, while elites were allowed to obtain dollars at a low exchange rate, whereas ordinary citizens faced the reality of a rapidly depreciating market exchange rate. The current market exchange rate is currently discounted by 40%.
When the country began printing lire to pay civil servants' salaries, depreciation would accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits (which account for more than 80% of all deposits) in lira, thereby creating the conditions for eliminating public debt through inflation.
By "liraizing" the debt reduction burden onto depositors through their shareholding, the banks' capital base is essentially spared.
If this situation becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class would be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The migration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant communities — upon which this system relies — will be harmed.
If the sect system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule a system of impoverished people, which can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
In the end, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
In contrast, the establishment of the new republic by the revolutionaries would take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance is far below its potential, and that performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, favoritism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a dynamic high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural power house, and create more synergies with immigrant communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement seeks to implement an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital, and forcibly reduce deposits of 1% of depositors whose deposits exceed 50% of the total deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be alleviated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle in the country's search for new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains uncertain.
